social_posts.post_text: Saturday is @fargojunkmarket Holiday Market from 9 am - 4 pm, which means I'm packing things up! I've got boxes and boxes of goodies to bring for the Holiday Junk Market. My website will be paused from now through the market, but I'll be ready to update the remaining inventory following the show this weekend for anyone who is too far to travel.

Weeks of hard work have led up to @fargojunkmarket Holiday Market. I really love this group of vases! You can see them TODAY 9 am - 4 pm at the Red River Valley Fairgrounds. {After today's market I'll update my website so online orders will make it for the holidays as well.}

A combination of the printing processes make the final surfaces of my work. Using thick underglaze, I screenprint my drawings as outlines onto newsprint and fill in the designs with colored slips working from foreground to background. The newsprint is then pressed and transferred to the clay surface, resulting in a one time unique print also called a monoprint. (Video by the amazing Penny of @northernstories)
.

Figuring out a method that worked for me to create the many designs I use on my work was a logistical challenge. Ultimately, I needed a method that would allow me to make several screens very cheaply, store them in a small studio space, and spend less time hand drawing each transfer. What ended up happening is my efficiency increased, my designs became more detailed, and the consistency followed. ⏳If only I knew this years ago! Want to learn what I do? Check out the link in my bio for more information about the Drawn to Screenprinting workshop I offer on my website.

I referenced this turkey hen design during my demo this morning. I did my normal process of creating underglaze lines and filling it in with colored slip on newsprint to get the turkey and foliage image. Then, I cut out a shape from the blue Tally Arch tissue @isla_transfers I designed to overlay on the body of the hen turkey. So many ways to use these transfers and make them your own.

I love a good tool and these little 2 oz squeeze bottles with removable tips are my favorite! I buy them in bulk (🔗 on my Amazon supply list). I have around 30 in the studio. Some for colored slip, some for underglaze, some for glaze, and some for attaching slip (for handles). I buy the tips in bulk too. Usually I use gauge 20 for small details (underglaze) and gauge 18 for most everything else. I also use a thicker gauge 14 for some of my thicker glaze. The removable tips are great because over time they can get clogged and corroded. The screw off tip makes it easy to clean and replace.
What's my most asked about tool? It these!

I've been on a slip casting journey for the past year or so. It's been way more challenging than I imagined it to be (mad props to all the slip casters out there, I am humbled), but it's also allowed me to focus on the parts of the process I enjoy most, which is the decorating. Here's a little bit of what it looks like. The liquid clay is poured into plaster molds. The plaster dries out the liquid and makes a "wall" of clay. The remainder of liquid clay slip is dumped back into the tank. Then the pieces are demolded and cleaned up.
(Also huge thank you to @ndsuinnovationstudio , @davemoneysign and @suppa.mane for their help in making this all a reality)

I cant believe how many years I worked in clay and I didn't do this this 🙈😬 Look at all that crud 😎 The most satisfying part of sieving is seeing this at the end. Makes it feel worth it. So many of the materials in ceramics come directly from the earth and have many impurities from the mines. This is a good example of why sieving is so important.

This week feels like the culmination of many hard weeks of work coming together. This is my final week of wet work before the Fall Sale Oct 6-8. I also unloaded a kiln of bisqueware that looks really good 🫶 Next week is all about firing, sanding, glazing, and firing some more. The cycle of doing the work of being an artist is a lot like a rollercoaster of ups and downs, but feels good to be on the up end right now after many challenges over the past few months. Feeling so grateful for this life and everyone's support now, in the past, and moving forward ❤️🙏

✨Meet Catie of Catie Miller Ceramics! 

"A playful approach to tableware."

🖌️Catie is a potter, illustrator, muralist, workshop instructor, and one-woman business. Featuring bold pops of color, whimsical designs, and oozing with fun, her brand Catie Miller Ceramics specializes in creating ceramic pieces for the home. Her shop includes everything from homemade ornaments and earrings to stickers and apparel!

⭐️ "Easy ordering process, fast proofing, fast shipping, and great product!" ⭐️

✅Catie has partnered with MakeStickers since 2020, trusting them to print her custom, die-cut stickers featuring her illustrations and, most recently, her branded packaging paper labels.

"Bright colors, playful patterning, and the unexpected."

☕️ When she's not creating a new ceramic table set or sketching a new sticker design, Catie can be found bringing beauty to public spaces in the form of joyful and vibrant murals.

Her mural work can be seen all over Fargo, North Dakota, where she is currently based.
